            <i>
              In addition to peace, prosperity has long been promised with
              democratization. Credits: Getty Images
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong> The what:</strong> Since World War II, the number of
            democratic states has risen while interstate wars have declined,
            suggesting a correlation between democracy and peace. However, as of
            2024, 72% of the global population is living under autocratic rule,
            which has seen a rise in the number of civil wars. This raises the
            question whether violence increases in pursuit of democracy and if
            countries should promote democracy.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The finding:</strong> Researchers assert that autocratic
            regimes face increased violence when they pursue democracy. They
            concluded that imposed democracy alone cannot bring peace; rather,
            international support and local actors' activism are necessary to
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-19-jul-25-analysis-h1-1-ensure-stable-democracy?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >ensure stable democracy</a
            >. Nepal, Burundi, and Liberia gained international support, which
            helped facilitate their democratization after conflict.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>Bigger picture:</strong> More Western democracies,
            especially the US, are scaling back their promotion of democracy
            abroad. They attach their geopolitical interests to democracy, which
            undermines the legitimacy and neutrality. Moreover, global trends
            showcase the rise of hybrid regimes. China stands out as an example
            where an autocratic regime with varying degrees of democratic
            policies has led to its economic growth.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
